  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Philadelphia who spent much of her life in a world where women were often told they weren’t cut out for technical fields, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat can shadow even the most capable minds. Stereotype threat is that quiet, persistent fear that your group’s stereotypes might influence your performance. In STEM, it’s the worry that as a woman, you might not be as good as men in math or science, which can make you doubt yourself in class or during exams. I remember when I was in school, my teachers would say things like, 'Girls aren’t built for engineering,' and even though I loved math, that comment made me hesitate. It’s not just about being told you’re not smart—it’s the constant anxiety that your presence might confirm a harmful belief about your abilities. Should we address it? Absolutely. We need to create spaces where people feel safe to explore their talents without fear of judgment. How? By changing the way we talk about STEM in schools and workplaces. Teachers can share stories of women who’ve succeeded in tech, and workplaces can have mentorship programs that pair students with role models. I’ve knitted and painted for decades, and I’ve learned that creativity and logic go hand in hand. Maybe that’s why I believe everyone has the potential to thrive in STEM if they feel supported. It’s not about fixing people—it’s about fixing the environment so that everyone can be their best selves.",
